Take a look at the [command pattern][1].

    // NOTE: code not tested, but I believe this is valid java...
    public class CommandExample 
    {
        public interface Command 
        {
            public void execute(Object data);
        }

        public class PrintCommand implements Command 
        {
            public void execute(Object data) 
            {
                System.out.println(data.toString());
            }    
        }

        public static void callCommand(Command command, Object data) 
        {
            command.execute(data);
        }

        public static void main(String... args) 
        {
            callCommand(new PrintCommand(), &quot;hello world&quot;);
        }
    }

*Edit:* as [Pete Kirkham points out][2], there&#39;s another way of doing this using a [Visitor][3]. The visitor approach is a little more involved - your nodes all need to be visitor-aware with an `acceptVisitor()` method - but if you need to traverse a more complex object graph then it&#39;s worth examining.


