To pass a method reference from class A to class B and then call the passed method in class A from class B, you can use functional interfaces and lambda expressions in Java. Here&#39;s an example.

**Class B**

Define a functional interface in class B that matches the signature of the method you want to pass from class A. Let&#39;s call it MethodInterface:

    public interface MethodInterface {
        void methodName();
    }

Still in class B, create a method that takes an instance of MethodInterface as a parameter and calls the method reference:


    public class B {
        public void callMethod(MethodInterface method) {
            method.methodName();
        }
    }

**Class A**

In class A, define the method you want to pass to class B. Make sure it matches the signature of the MethodInterface:


    public class A {
        public void methodToPass() {
            System.out.println(&quot;Method called from class B&quot;);
        }
    }

Still in class A, create an instance of class B and pass a method reference to methodToPass using a lambda expression:


    public class A {
        public void methodToPass() {
            System.out.println(&quot;Method called from class B&quot;);
        }
    
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            A objA = new A();
            B objB = new B();
    
            objB.callMethod(objA::methodToPass);
        }
    }

In this example, `objA::methodToPass` is a method reference that refers to the `methodToPass` method in class A. It is passed to the `callMethod` method in class B, which then calls the method reference, resulting in the execution of `methodToPass` in class A.

Note that the `::` operator is used to create a method reference. The syntax `objA::methodToPass` is equivalent to creating an anonymous inner class that implements the `MethodInterface` and calls `methodToPass` on the provided instance of class A.

